Gross Revenue Prediction using Liner Regression

Gross Revenue Prediction using Liner Regression

Part I - Data Analysis

1. Objective

Objective of this project is to help a studio in priortization (such as decide which titles to fund for production, how much to bid on produced movies, when to release a title, how much to invest in marketing and PR, etc.) by investigating the relationship between the movie descriptors and the success of the movie at box office which is represented as Gross Revenue. This analysis is very valuable after the movie is already released as it can affect additional marketing spend or how much a studio should negotiate with on-demand streaming companies etc.

2. About Dataset

Dataset has 40K rows and 39 columns which contains information about movies, including ratings, budget, gross revenue and other attributes. It was prepared by by querying IMDbs API (see www.omdbapi.com) and joining it with a separate dataset of movie budgets and gross earnings (unknown to you). The join key was the movie title. Each row represents a movie title and each column represents a descriptor such as Title, Actors, and Budget.

3.2 Data Analysis: Popular Genres

The column Genre represents a list of genres associated with the movie in a string format. Below code parses each text string into a binary vector with 1s representing the presence of a genre and 0s the absence and add it to the dataframe as additional columns. Code removes the original Genre column.

For example, if there are a total of 3 genres: Drama, Comedy, and Action, a movie that is both Action and Comedy should be represented by a binary vector <0, 1, 1>.

genreCorpus = Corpus(VectorSource(df2$Genre))
genreCorpus = tm_map(genreCorpus, content_transformer(tolower))
genreCorpus = tm_map(genreCorpus, removeWords, c("N/A"))
genreCorpus = tm_map(genreCorpus, removePunctuation)

genreDocumentTermMatrix = DocumentTermMatrix(genreCorpus)
genreMatrix = as.data.frame(as.matrix(genreDocumentTermMatrix))
df2 <- cbind(df2, genreMatrix)


# Plot the relative proportions of movies having the top 10 most common genres.


# Select movies from top 10 most common genres and plot their relative proportions
top10 <- (sort(colSums(genreMatrix), decreasing = TRUE)[1:10])
top10names <- names(sort(colSums(genreMatrix), decreasing = TRUE)[1:10])
dfTop10 <- data.frame(top10names, top10)

genreFreq <- colSums(as.matrix(genreDocumentTermMatrix))
genreFreqSort <- sort(genreFreq,decreasing = TRUE)[1:10]

dfGFreq <- data.frame(names(genreFreqSort), genreFreqSort/sum(genreFreqSort))
names(dfGFreq) = c("Genre","Frequency")

ggplot(data=dfGFreq, aes(x=dfGFreq$Genre)) +

From the above distribution plot, it is very clear that the top genres with highest proportions are Comedy and Drama which is liked by majority of the population. In addition to these 2 genres, short, action and romance movies have considerably high proportions compared to the rest of the movie genres.

3.3 Data Analysis: Eliminate mismatched rows

The dataframe was put together by merging two different sources of data and it is possible that the merging process was inaccurate in some cases (the merge was done based on movie title, but there are cases of different movies with the same title). There are 3 columns that contain date information: Year (numeric year), Date (numeric year), and Released (string representation of the release date).

Below code finds and removes all rows where merge error might have occurred based on a mismatch between these variables. To make sure subsequent analysis and modeling work well, code avoids removing more than 10% of the rows that have a Gross value present.

# Remove rows with Year/Date/Released mismatch
check <-function(Year, Date, ReleasedYear){
  
  if((is.na(Year) && is.na(Date) && is.na(ReleasedYear)) || 
     (is.na(Year) && is.na(Date)) ||
     (is.na(Date) && is.na(ReleasedYear)) || 
     (is.na(Year) && is.na(ReleasedYear))
  ){
    return(TRUE)
    
  }else if(is.na(Year) && !(is.na(Date)) && !(is.na(ReleasedYear))){
    if(Date == ReleasedYear){
      return(TRUE)
      
    }else{
      return(FALSE)
    }
  }else if(!(is.na(Year)) && is.na(Date) && !(is.na(ReleasedYear))){
    if(Year == ReleasedYear){
      return(TRUE)
      
    }else{
      return(FALSE)
    }
  }else if(!(is.na(Year)) && !(is.na(Date)) && is.na(ReleasedYear)){
    if(Date == Year){
      return(TRUE)
      
    }else{
      return(FALSE)
    }
  }else{
    if((Date == Year) || (Year == ReleasedYear) || (Date == ReleasedYear)){
      return(TRUE)
    }else{
      return(FALSE)
    }
  }
  
}

dfYear <- df2[mapply(check, as.numeric(df2$Year), as.numeric(df2$Date), 
                     as.numeric(format(as.Date(df2$Released, format="%Y-%m-%d"),"%Y"))),]
cat("Remaining Record Count: ", as.character(nrow(dfYear)))
## Remaining Record Count:  34972
A speareted function check() was created which accepts Year, Date, ReleasedYear for each record and returns True if Year not macthing across all three variables. Function consists of set of if else loops which has following logic -
  • If all 3 values are NA then return TRUE
  • If 2 values are NA then reurn TRUE
  • If one value is NA then check Year in other two values. If both Years are same return True else False.
  • If none of the values are NA, then check Year for all three values. If any two Years are same return True else False.

3.5 Data Analysis: Awards

The column Awards describes nominations and awards in text format. Below code converts it to 2 numeric columns, the first capturing the number of wins, and the second capturing nominations. Code replaces the Awards column with these new columns and then study the relationship of Gross revenue with respect to them.

# Convert Awards to 2 numeric columns: wins and nominations
dfAwNom <- data.frame()
for(i in seq(length(df2$Awards))){
  wins = 0
  nomi = 0
  
  string <- strsplit(df2$Awards[i], split="[.&]")
  for (sent in string[[1]]) {
    if (grepl("win", tolower(sent)) || grepl("won", tolower(sent))){
      wins = wins + as.numeric(gsub("[[:alpha:]]", "", sent))
    }else if(grepl("nominat", tolower(sent))){
      nomi = nomi + as.numeric(gsub("[[:alpha:]]", "", sent))
    }
  }
  
  dfAwNom <- rbind(dfAwNom,c(wins,wins+nomi))
}

dfAwNom <- cbind(df2$Gross, dfAwNom)
colnames(dfAwNom)<-c("Gross", "Wins","Nominations")

cat("Record Count with Valid wins/nominations: ", as.character(nrow(dfAwNom[(dfAwNom$Nominations>0),])))
## Record Count with Valid wins/nominations:  14727
Following strategy was used to capture wins and nominations -
  • Initailize win and nominate variables to 0
  • Loop through each row and get string from Awards column.
  • Split string using either . or &
  • Convert each substring to lowercase
  • If substring has win/won, remove all alphbets and increament wins variable by digits in remaining string
  • If substring has nominat, remove all alphbets and increament nominate variable by digits in remaining string 
# Plot Gross revenue against wins and nominations

dfAwNom <- dfAwNom[!is.na(dfAwNom$Gross),]

ggplot(dfAwNom, aes(x=dfAwNom$Gross, y=dfAwNom$Wins)) + geom_point(aes(y=dfAwNom$Wins, color="Wins"), size = 2)+ geom_smooth(se=F) + labs(title="Gross Revenue vs Wins", x="Gross", y="Wins")+ ylim(0, 50)

ggplot(dfAwNom, aes(x=dfAwNom$Gross, y=dfAwNom$Nominations)) + geom_point(aes(y=dfAwNom$Nominations, color="Nominations"), size = 2)+ geom_smooth(se=F) + labs(title="Gross Revenue vs Nominations", x="Gross", y="Nominations")+ ylim(0, 50)

From the above scatter plot, we can see both Wins and Nominations seem to have slightly positive correlation with gross revenue. Gross Revenue tends to increase with number of wins and nominations received but after a certain number of awards (>25 or so) slope of this relationship becomes less steep.

3.6 Data Analysis: Rating

There are several variables that describe ratings, including IMDb ratings (imdbRating represents average user ratings and imdbVotes represents the number of user ratings), and multiple Rotten Tomatoes ratings (represented by several variables pre-fixed by tomato). Below code investigates the pairwise relationships between these different descriptors using plots.

# Illustrate how ratings from IMDb and Rotten Tomatoes are related

ggplot(subset(df2, !is.na(imdbVotes) & !is.na(imdbRating)), aes(x = imdbVotes, y = imdbRating)) + geom_point(color="dodgerblue") + labs(title = "IMDB User Rating vs. IMDB Votes", x = "# of votes", y = "IMDB User Rating")

ggplot(subset(df2, !is.na(tomatoReviews) & !is.na(tomatoRating)), aes(x = tomatoReviews, y = tomatoRating))+ geom_point(color="darkred") + labs(title = "RottenTomatoes Critic Rating vs. RottenTomatoes Review Count", x = "# of reviews", y = "RT Critic Rating")

ratingcols = c("imdbRating", "tomatoMeter","tomatoRating", "tomatoUserMeter","tomatoUserRating") 

ggpairs(df2, lower = list(continuous = wrap("points", color = "red", alpha = 0.5), 
                          combo = wrap("box", color = "orange", alpha = 0.3), 
                          discrete = wrap("facetbar", color = "yellow", alpha = 0.3) ), 
        diag = list(continuous = wrap("densityDiag",  color = "blue", alpha = 0.5) ), 
        ratingcols)+ 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1))

Due to positive correlations between IMDB and Rotten Tomatoes plots it can be cloncluded that there is a general consensus about how movies are rated. Each pairwise graph shows a fairly broad line, though, so there is still a good amount of variability present.

There is also a conspicuous line along the x-axis of the imdbRating vs.tomatoUserRating graph, possibly indicating review bombing from upset users. The other two graphs relating review count to rating show an interesting, but understandble trend: IMDB ratings are more closely related to number of IMDB reviews than RT Critic ratings are to number of RT Critic reviews.

This is likely because IMDB users are more likely to self-select movies they think they will enjoy, while the job of a critic is to watch a wide variety of movies and remain as unbiased as possible.

3.7 Data Analysis: Rating vs Awards

These ratings typically reflect the general appeal of the movie to the public or gather opinions from a larger body of critics. Whereas awards are given by professional societies that may evaluate a movie on specific attributes, such as artistic performance, screenplay, sound design, etc. Below code study the relationship between ratings and awards using graphs (awards here refers to wins and/or nominations).

# Show how ratings and awards are related
dfRateAwNom <- data.frame()
for(i in seq(length(df2$Awards))){
  wins = 0
  nomi = 0
  
  string <- strsplit(df2$Awards[i], split="[.&]")
  for (sent in string[[1]]) {
    if (grepl("win", tolower(sent)) || grepl("won", tolower(sent))){
      wins = wins + as.numeric(gsub("[[:alpha:]]", "", sent))
    }else if(grepl("nominat", tolower(sent))){
      nomi = nomi + as.numeric(gsub("[[:alpha:]]", "", sent))
    }
  }
  
  dfRateAwNom <- rbind(dfRateAwNom,c(wins,wins+nomi))
}

dfRateAwNom <- cbind(df2$tomatoRating, df2$tomatoUserRating, df2$imdbRating, df2$imdbVotes, dfRateAwNom)
colnames(dfRateAwNom)<-c("TomatoRating", "TomatoUserRating", "ImdbRating", "ImdbVotes", 
                         "Wins","Nominations")

ggplot(dfRateAwNom, aes(dfRateAwNom$TomatoRating)) + 
  geom_point(data=dfRateAwNom, aes(y=dfRateAwNom$Wins, color="Wins")) + 
  geom_point(data=dfRateAwNom, aes(y=dfRateAwNom$Nominations, color="Nomination")) + 
  labs(title="Tomato Rating for Wins & Nominations", x="Tomato Rating", y="Wins & Nominations")

ggplot(dfRateAwNom, aes(dfRateAwNom$TomatoUserRating)) + 
  geom_point(data=dfRateAwNom, aes(y=dfRateAwNom$Wins, color="Wins")) + 
  geom_point(data=dfRateAwNom, aes(y=dfRateAwNom$Nominations, color="Nomination")) + 
  labs(title="Tomato User Rating for Wins & Nominations", x="Tomato User Rating", y="Wins & Nominations")

ggplot(dfRateAwNom, aes(dfRateAwNom$ImdbRating)) + 
  geom_point(data=dfRateAwNom, aes(y=dfRateAwNom$Wins, color="Wins")) + 
  geom_point(data=dfRateAwNom, aes(y=dfRateAwNom$Nominations, color="Nomination")) + 
  labs(title="IMDB Rating for Wins & Nominations", x="IMDB Rating", y="Wins & Nominations")

ggplot(dfRateAwNom, aes(dfRateAwNom$ImdbVotes)) + 
  geom_point(data=dfRateAwNom, aes(y=dfRateAwNom$Wins, color="Wins")) + 
  geom_point(data=dfRateAwNom, aes(y=dfRateAwNom$Nominations, color="Nomination")) + 
  labs(title="IMDB Votes for Wins & Nominations", x="IMDB Votes", y="Wins & Nominations")

ggpairs(dfRateAwNom, lower = list(continuous = wrap("points", color = "red", alpha = 0.5), 
                                  combo = wrap("box", color = "orange", alpha = 0.3), 
                                  discrete = wrap("facetbar", color = "yellow", alpha = 0.3) ), 
        diag = list(continuous = wrap("densityDiag",  color = "blue", alpha = 0.5) ), 
        columns=c("TomatoRating", "TomatoUserRating", "ImdbRating", "ImdbVotes", "Wins", "Nominations"))+ 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1))

As it can be seen in scatterplots above, Win and/or Nominations increases as Rating increases but the correlation between the two is not very strong. We can infer that, with the (Wins > 0, Nominations > 0) combination showing ratings above 70%, imdbRating, TomatoMeter, TomatoRating and TomatoUserMeter are the candidates that can help predict if a movie will succeed.
